article.description: Steve Francis had another streaky night but scored 13 of his 21 points in the third quarter, hitting 6-of-7 in the period, as the Houston Rockets beat the slumping Seattle SuperSonics 83-72 on Friday night.
article.headline: Rockets heap more misery on slumping Sonics
article.linkText: Francis' third-quarter surge sends Rockets past Sonics
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Even though he's not hitting everything he puts up these days, Steve Francis has no plans to stop shooting. Francis had another streaky night but scored 13 of his 21 points in the third quarter, hitting 6-of-7 in the period, as the Houston Rockets beat the slumping Seattle SuperSonics 83-72 on Friday night. "I'm going to keep shooting, whether it goes in or not,'' said Francis, who had hit 39 percent in his five previous games. "I have to keep the defense honest. Making 7-of-8 in the quarter or whatever I made, I felt pretty good about it.'' Glen Rice and Kenny Thomas each added 12 points for Houston, but the Sonics did plenty to beat themselves. Seattle lost its third straight, shooting 37 percent and posting season lows with the 72 points and 26 second-half points. "We're shooting awful,'' said Rashard Lewis, who scored 18 points. "It just wasn't there for us tonight. No rhythm.'' It spoiled a milestone night for point guard Gary Payton, who scored 10 points on 3-of-16 shooting as he became Seattle's franchise leader with 964 regular-season games, passing Fred Brown, who played from 1971-84. Payton, who had 14 assists, left without speaking to reporters. "People have bad games,'' said Francis, who missed 13 of his 21 shots. "He's been in the league 13 years. Everybody's entitled to a bad shooting night.'' Desmond Mason had 19 points for the Sonics, who have lost six of their last seven after opening the season 8-2. "Both ends of the floor, we need work,'' Seattle coach Nate McMillan said. Francis found his touch after halftime. Yao Ming attracted the defense inside then kicked it out to the perimeter as the Rockets turned their 46-36 deficit into a 68-57 lead entering the fourth. Yao scored only six points, well under the 15.2 he averaged over the previous five games. But his nimble passing was a huge difference, as he fed the ball to open men like Francis, Rice and Moochie Norris. "I'm not the final stop for the ball,'' Yao said through a translator. "When the ball comes my way, I look to pass it.'' Seattle's 11 third-quarter points were a season low. "We didn't run the offense,'' Lewis said. "We were just going through the motions.'' Despite their woeful second half, the Sonics were still in it midway through the fourth quarter. Lewis hit two free throws to trim the deficit to 72-66 with 5:20 remaining. Mason's jumper from the left corner got Seattle to 78-72 with 1:09 to play, but Norris took a feed from Yao and nailed a 17-footer with 44.7 seconds on the clock. Norris and Francis made three of four free throws down the stretch. "Yao's passing was phenomenal,'' Houston coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. "He really got us going there and then Steve got it going. But I shouldn't even bring up those things. Defense won this game for us -- 26 points in the second half.'' The Sonics were in great shape after a super second quarter by Mason, who scored six points during a 12-0 run that gave Seattle a 38-29 lead with 3:39 left before halftime. It was 46-36 at the break, but that's when Francis took over and Seattle went flat. "It's obvious that we're not playing good basketball right now,'' McMillan said.

Game notes
Houston G Tito Maddox made his NBA debut, if you can call it that. He got off the bench for 2.4 seconds at the end of the first quarter. ... Payton missed his first six shots, all in the first quarter. ... Tomjanovich is three victories from tying Alex Hannum (471) for 24th place on the NBA's career list. ... Yao received a big cheer during pregame introductions.
